				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: TD and mobs <a name="5797"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 28 03 12:44 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Short answer... Don't kite casters. Period.
<br />

<br />
If you do, get one, likely you will die because a snared/rooted bard is a dead bard, in any kiting.  Thus the reason that there are so few good swarm spots. You need no casters and limited roamers.
<br />

<br />
As for no luck swarm kiting. I failed (run to zone or deaths) more times than I'd like to mention, at least two dozen... And that's after leveling a quad kiting druid to 54.  The trick is to find a low lag zone with well grouped mobs and a great large open mob-free kiting area.  The answer always comes back to EW in the NE corner.  You can pull a handful of mobs that run the same speed, are fairly social (they'll help a friend that is being attacked rather than follow some silly bard running away from them), have mobs with relatively few hps and best of all is within easy selos distance from a zoneline.
<br />

<br />
That being said, I wouldn't do much swarm kiting until you have at least two real chants (bellow doesn't count due to the short range, though it works).  That used to mean 36 when you get your Chant of Flame but not sure you don't get another one sooner now.  That way you have Futils and CoF to chant down the former pet.  I have heard of it being done at 27, but at that point I was still in my Fear-kiting years.
<br />

<br />
Hope that helps,
<br />

<br />
Sinfonian</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
